      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Fix Doubao false 100% request usage",
        "body": "## Problem\n\n@foobra reported on PR #498 that the Doubao usage card always shows 100% used. Volcano Ark can return HTTP 200 with a complete request-limit pair where `limit > 0` and `remaining = 0`, while later requests still succeed. Treating that single response as exhaustion produces a false 100% card.\n\nFixes #1382.\n\n## Solution\n\n- Confirm an ambiguous successful zero-remaining response with one immediate probe using the same model.\n- If the confirmation is another HTTP 200 with zero remaining, mark the request-limit headers unreliable and show the existing `Active - check dashboard for details` fallback.\n- If confirmation returns HTTP 429, preserve genuine exhaustion. A 429 carrying request-limit headers is also treated as request-bucket exhaustion.\n- Require trustworthy request-limit evidence before rendering a percentage. Bare standalone 429 responses remain on the active fallback because they can describe another throttle.\n- Propagate task and URL cancellation. If ordinary confirmation fails, conservatively preserve the initial exhausted snapshot.\n- Log the repeated HTTP 200 unreliable-header pattern for diagnostics.\n\n## Testing\n\n- `swift test --filter Doubao`: 17 tests across 3 suites passed.\n- Added transport-level coverage for repeated HTTP 200, HTTP 200 followed by explicit or headerless 429, standalone bare/partial 429, confirmation failure, and both cancellation forms.\n- `make check`: SwiftFormat clean; SwiftLint 0 violations across 1026 files.\n- Branch autoreview: clean, no accepted/actionable findings, correctness confidence 0.88.\n\nGitHub CI is the final full-suite merge gate after this rewritten head.\n\n## Scope\n\nThe exact Volcano account-tier matrix remains provider-controlled. The repeated-success warning keeps the condition observable without exposing credentials or account data.\n",
        "branch": "fix/doubao-100-percent-display",
